      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Settlement Adjustments When Selling in Queensland: What to Expect
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Settlement adjustments are one of the last things sellers think about and one of the first to cause confusion on settlement day. Here is how they work and what to watch for.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you sell a property in Queensland, the final amount you receive at settlement is rarely the exact contract price. It is the contract price, adjusted for a range of ongoing costs that are apportioned between you and the buyer as at the settlement date. This process is called settlement adjustments, and while your solicitor handles the calculations, understanding what is being adjusted and why helps you read your settlement statement clearly and spot errors before they become problems.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What settlement adjustments are</h2>
      <p>Most property ownership costs are billed in advance: council rates quarterly, water rates quarterly or annually, body corporate levies quarterly or annually. When you sell, you will often have pre-paid some portion of a billing period that extends beyond your settlement date. The buyer is taking ownership partway through that billing period, so they owe you a reimbursement for the days they benefit from your pre-payment.</p>

      <p>The logic works in reverse too. If a billing period started before settlement and you have not yet paid the bill, the amount owing up to settlement is your responsibility and will be deducted from your proceeds at settlement to clear the debt before the buyer takes title.</p>

      <p>Adjustments do not change the contract price. They are applied on top of it, increasing or decreasing the net amount you receive depending on the timing of pre-payments and arrears. Your solicitor itemises each adjustment in a settlement statement, and both parties (or their legal representatives) must agree on the figures before settlement proceeds.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Which costs are adjusted at settlement</h2>
      <p>Council rates are the most common adjustment. Brisbane City Council issues rates quarterly. If you have paid a full quarter's rates and settlement falls mid-quarter, the buyer reimburses you for the remaining days of the quarter. If rates are in arrears, the unpaid portion is deducted from your proceeds.</p>

      <p>Water rates and usage charges are adjusted similarly. The relevant authority reads the meter at or near settlement, and usage up to settlement is your responsibility. Fixed access charges are apportioned by the day.</p>

      <p>Body corporate levies are adjusted for strata and community title properties in the same way as council rates. If you have paid the quarterly levy for a period that extends beyond settlement, the buyer reimburses you for their days. Admin and sinking fund contributions are typically included in this adjustment.</p>

      <p>Land tax adjustments apply in Queensland in limited circumstances. Queensland land tax is assessed on 30 June each year based on the landholding of the registered owner at that date. If settlement occurs before 30 June and the buyer will be the registered owner on 30 June, the land tax liability for the full year is technically the buyer's, but in practice solicitors often negotiate an adjustment that reflects both parties' respective periods of ownership. This is more common with investment property sales than owner-occupied homes, where principal place of residence exemptions typically apply.</p>

      <p>Rental income is adjusted if the property is sold with a tenant in place. If rent has been paid in advance to cover days after settlement, that portion is deducted from the seller's proceeds and credited to the buyer, since the buyer will be entitled to that rent as the incoming landlord. If rent is in arrears at settlement, the position is more complex and typically handled between solicitors.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the daily rate calculation works</h2>
      <p>The mechanics are straightforward. Your solicitor takes the total charge for a billing period, divides it by the number of days in that period, and multiplies by the relevant number of days to produce the adjustment amount.</p>

      <p>For example: if council rates for the March quarter are $600, covering 91 days, the daily rate is approximately $6.59. If settlement falls on day 30 of the quarter, the seller has been responsible for 29 days and the buyer is responsible for 62 days. The buyer reimburses the seller $6.59 multiplied by 62 days, which is approximately $409. This amount is added to the settlement proceeds the seller receives.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor prepares a formal settlement statement with each adjustment itemised. You should receive this statement several days before settlement, giving you time to query any figures that do not look right. The most common errors are using the wrong billing period dates, applying a rate that has since been updated, or omitting an adjustment altogether.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Your responsibility before and after settlement</h2>
      <p>As the seller, you are responsible for all costs and liabilities up to and including the settlement date. The buyer becomes responsible from the day after settlement. Adjustments are the mechanism that turns this principle into specific dollar amounts, but the underlying rule is simple: the seller bears costs for their period of ownership, and the buyer bears costs for theirs.</p>

      <p>This responsibility allocation extends to things like electricity and gas (where the seller arranges a final meter reading and account closure, and the buyer opens new accounts from settlement date) and council rates (where the council is notified of the ownership change and issues future notices to the buyer). Adjustments cover the billing period overlaps; ongoing billing responsibility shifts entirely at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How your solicitor handles the adjustments</h2>
      <p>Your conveyancer or solicitor is responsible for preparing the settlement statement, checking figures with the buyer's solicitor, and reconciling the final amounts before settlement proceeds. In Queensland, most residential settlements are now conducted electronically through the PEXA platform, where adjustments are built into the settlement figures and the net proceeds are transferred to the seller on settlement day.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor should provide you with a preliminary settlement statement a few days before settlement so you can review the figures. Check that the billing periods are correct, that the rates figures match your actual bills, and that any rental income adjustment reflects what was actually received and what period it covers. If you have any arrears on rates or charges, confirm with your solicitor that these are being cleared from settlement proceeds so you do not receive a debt notice after the sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common settlement adjustment surprises and how to avoid them</h2>
      <p>The most common surprise for sellers is discovering that unpaid council rates or an outstanding water bill is being deducted from settlement proceeds at a higher amount than expected. Rates can accumulate quickly if left unattended during a campaign period, and the interest charges on overdue accounts add up. Checking your rates account shortly before settlement, rather than assuming everything is current, avoids last-minute surprises.</p>

      <p>Body corporate sellers sometimes underestimate the impact of a recently issued special levy. If the body corporate has resolved a special levy that covers a period including post-settlement days, your solicitor needs to know about this to adjust correctly. Ask your body corporate manager for the most current levy schedule before your solicitor prepares the settlement statement.</p>

      <p>Sellers of tenanted properties occasionally overlook the rental adjustment entirely, particularly if settlement proceeds quickly after an offer is accepted. If your tenant has paid rent in advance, a meaningful credit may be owed to the buyer, and missing this can lead to a dispute after settlement.</p>

